description: luciferin 4-monooxygenase from common eastern firefly. Produces green light with a wavelength of 562 nm. Most commonly used luciferase reporter.
shipped as: Purified Plasmid DNA, Stained with Cresol Red
citations: Cloning of firefly luciferase cDNA and the expression of active luciferase in Escherichia coli. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 1985 Dec;82(23):7870-3. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3906652

description: Luciferase from Gaussia princeps. At 19kD, it is the smallest known luciferase and its catalytic properties make it one of the brightest known. Additionally, multiple disulfide bonds contribute to the protein stability at elevated temperatures. The first report of in vivo imaging using Gluc demonstrated sensitivity that is several orders of magnitude higher than the first generation luciferases, Firefly (Fluc) and Renilla lucifereses
shipped as: Purified Plasmid DNA, Stained with Cresol Red

description: 36kDa protein from sea pansy (Renilla reniformis). It produces a blue light of 480nm, and it requires only coelenterazine and oxygen. It can be used in dual-reporter assays with Firefly luciferase due to their differences in substrate requirements and light output.
shipped as: Purified Plasmid DNA, Stained with Cresol Red
citations: Isolation and expression of a cDNA encoding Renilla reniformis luciferase. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 1991 May 15;88(10):4438-42. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1674607
